Dr '''Judy Franz''' is an American physicist; graduating from [[Cornell University]] in 1959 with a B.A degree in Physics.<ref name="CSWP article">{{cite journal|title=Judy Franz Named Executive Officer of APS|journal=CSWP|date=Spring 1994|volume=14|issue=1|pages=1,20,21|url=http://www.aps.org/programs/women/reports/gazette/upload/spring94.pdf#zoom=100}}</ref> Judy then followed her interest in physics and received an MS in 1961 and a PhD in 1965 from the [[University of Illinois]].<ref name="alumni illinois">{{cite web|title=Distinguished Alumni Awards|url=https://engineering.illinois.edu/engage/distinguished-alumni-and-friends/distinguished/article/5658|website=University of Illinois}}</ref> After this, she became a post-doc at the IBM research laboratory in Zurich, Switzerland from 1965 to 1967, before returning to America to work at the physics department of [[Indiana University]] for 18 years. <ref name="CSWP article"/>

Along with publishing a number of high profile articles in her research of condensed matter physics,<ref>{{cite web|title=CWP at physics.UCLA.edu|url=http://cwp.library.ucla.edu/Phase2/Franz,_Judy_R.@921234567.html#sip}}</ref> Judy was a key advocate of improving physics education. She received the [[Melba Newell Phillips Medal]] for Creative Leadership in Physics Education from the [[The American Association of Physics Teachers]] (AAPT).<ref name="phillips medal">{{cite web|title=Franz Awarded Phillips Medal|url=http://www.aapt.org/aboutaapt/Franz_Awarded_Phillips_Medal.cfm|website=American Association of Physics Teachers|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> She served as Executive Officer of the American Physical Society <ref name="CSWP article"/> for 15 years<ref name="judy franz blog">{{cite web|website=https://ggstem.wordpress.com/2013/06/04/judy-franz/}}</ref>, encouraging more women to take up physics. <ref name="CSWP article"/> She is now retired. <ref name="judy franz blog"/>

